Near Banbridge Town, in the county town, one morning in July
Down a boring green came, a sweet Colleen, and she smiled as she passed me by
She looked so sweet, from her two white feet, to the sheen of her nut brown hair
Such a coaxing elf, I had to shake my soul, to make sure I was standing there
From Boundary Bay up to Derry Cray, and from Gateway to Dublin Town
No maid I've seen like the sweet Colleen, that I met in the county town
As she on one spat, I shook my head, and I gazed with a feeling rare
And I said, says I, to a passer-by, who's a maid with a nut brown hair
He smiled at me, and with pride says he, that's a gem of Ireland's crown
She's young Rosie McCann, from the banks of the Bann, she's the star of the county town
From Boundary Bay up to Derry Cray, and from Gateway to Dublin Town
No maid I've seen like the sweet Colleen, that I met in the county town
At the Crossroads Fair, I'll be surely there, and I'll dress in my Sunday clothes
And I'll try sheep's eyes, and be lootering lice, on the hurl of a nut brown rose
No pipe I'll smoke, no horse I'll joke, though it's rust, my clout turns brown
Can I, smiling bright, by my own fire sight, set the star of the county down
